Here is a simple, bad financial product:=09You give me $100.=09In a year, I=
 give you back the return on the S&P 500 stock index, but (1) if the index =
is=C2=A0down, you don=E2=80=99t lose any money and just get your $100 back,=
 and (2) if the index is up more than 5%, you only get the first 5% of retu=
rns. If the S&P goes up 3%, you get $103=C2=A0back. If it goes up 5%, you g=
et $105. If it goes up 37%, you get $105. If it goes down 5%, you get $100.=
 If it goes down 37%, you get $100.You have bought 100% downside protection=
 by giving away the upside above 105%.=C2=A0How do I manufacture this produ=
ct? That is, how do I make sure that I have enough money in every scenario =
to pay you back? Well, I could probably do some stuff with options. But the=
 simplest and most obvious approach is:=09I use your $100 to buy a one-year=
 Treasury bill, which pays roughly 5.1% interest.=09In a year I have $105.1=
0.=09At that point, I look at the return on the S&P. If it=E2=80=99s 5% or =
more, I give you $105 and keep the remaining $0.10. If it=E2=80=99s zero or=
 negative, I give you $100 and keep the remaining $5.10. In between, I give=
 you $100 plus the S&P=E2=80=99s return and keep the rest.This is, like I s=
aid, a very bad product. You should not buy it; you should just buy the Tre=
asury bill yourself instead. But the point I want to make is that=C2=A0thre=
e years ago=C2=A0I could not have offered you even this product. Back then,=
 the one-year Treasury rate was something like 0.08%. If I had wanted to of=
fer you a product that was =E2=80=9Cthe S&P return, but you can=E2=80=99t l=
ose money and your upside is capped,=E2=80=9D the cap on your upside would =
have been, you know, 0.08%, which is even less exciting than 5%.=C2=A0The p=
oint is that for a long time interest rates were very low, which means that=
 if you wanted to make a return on your money you needed to take stock-like=
 risks: You could buy the S&P 500, make money if it went up, and lose money=
 if it went down. But now interest rates are considerably higher, which mea=
ns that if you want to make a (nominal) return on your money you can do tha=
t without taking any risk at all.
  [1]
One thing this means is that you can just buy bonds, but that=E2=80=99s bor=
ing. Another, much more fun thing that it means is that financial product d=
esigners=C2=A0have a lot more to work with. My product above is absurd, but=
 you could use options to build more plausible products, and if you do that=
, the fact that the risk-free rate is 5% makes your product much more attra=
ctive than it would have been at 0%. So the Wall Street Journal reports:Eve=
n as signs of cooling inflation have powered major indexes to new highs, in=
vestors have poured billions into exchange-traded funds that use derivative=
s to produce extra dividend income or protect against losses.Such funds, wh=
ich were almost nonexistent four years ago, give retirees and other investo=
rs the chance to chase stock returns while also protecting against a potent=
ial market slide. The funds have taken in at least $31 billion of new inves=
tor money over the past 12 months, according to FactSet, bringing their tot=
al assets to almost $120 billion. ...Buffer funds, another popular strategy=
 that uses derivatives, claim to guard against investor losses, up to a poi=
nt, while limiting potential gains as well. A similar class of funds even a=
dvertises 100% downside protection, when certain conditions are met.=E2=80=
=9CWe like to call this kind of stuff =E2=80=98boomer candy,=E2=80=99 =E2=
=80=9D said Eric Balchunas, senior ETF analyst at Bloomberg Intelligence. =
=E2=80=9CThey like being in the stock market but want the protection that h=
elps you sleep at night. A good chunk of the ETF industry is in the lab try=
ing to design more of these funds as we speak.=E2=80=9DWe talked about the =
100% downside protection funds last summer. Schematically, the way to get 1=
00% downside protection is to (1) take $100, (2) invest $95 in Treasury bil=
ls that will pay off $100 in a year, and (3) spend the remaining $5 buying =
options on the S&P 500 that will pay off if the index goes up.
  [2]
 This gives you some of the return of the S&P 500, but with a guaranteed re=
turn of your principal. But when rates were zero, that sentence would have =
read =E2=80=9C(1) take $100, (2) invest $100 in Treasury bills that will pa=
y off $100 in a year, and (3) that=E2=80=99s it, you=E2=80=99re out of mone=
y, there=E2=80=99s no way to get anything like equity returns with no downs=
ide risk.=E2=80=9D Now there is.In some sense this is all sleight of hand. =
=E2=80=9CYou always get your money back=E2=80=9D is a very=C2=A0optically=
=C2=A0attractive pitch, and it is possible now in a way that it wasn=E2=80=
=99t three years ago. But it is=C2=A0less economically=C2=A0attractive=C2=
=A0now than it was three years ago, because now the risk-free alternative i=
s not =E2=80=9Cyou put in $100 and get back $100=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=
=9Cyou put in $100 and get back $105.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And with risk-free rate=
s high, expected stock returns should also be high, so giving up upside is =
more costly:One such fund [retired financial adviser Craig Morningstar] own=
s from First Trust tracks the Nasdaq-100. Over a rolling one-year period, t=
he fund aims to protect against the first 10% slide in the index, meaning t=
hat if Nasdaq-100 dropped 15%, the fund would be down about 5%. Investor ga=
ins are capped at roughly 20%.=C2=A0But with the Nasdaq-100 up 37% over the=
 past 12 months, buffer fund investors have missed out on substantial retur=
ns.Still, you can see why the ETF industry is in the lab. The lab was so bo=
ring for so long, and now it isn=E2=80=99t. Investors got used to the idea =
that the only way to get a return=C2=A0was by owning stocks, so now they wa=
nt to own stocks, but with less risk. And with interest rates higher, there=
 are ways to do that.=C2=A0
