   =20
      CEO school
   =20
 =20
You could have a model of Harvard Business School that is like:=09Harvard B=
usiness School teaches you skills that would make you good at running a com=
pany.=09There are lots of companies that could use those skills.=09But you =
don=E2=80=99t want to run those companies, because they make, like, ball be=
arings.=09You=C2=A0want to run a=C2=A0fancy=C2=A0company; you want to run a=
 hedge fund or a tech startup or something.=09Meanwhile, the people current=
ly running the ball bearings company would not be all that excited about=C2=
=A0you, a fresh-faced business school graduate who has never run anything, =
coming in to run their company, even if you did learn a lot of useful skill=
s at Harvard.=09Therefore various industries exist whose principal business=
 is=C2=A0laundering=C2=A0ball bearings companies=C2=A0into opportunities th=
at appeal to Harvard Business School graduates. You wrap the ball bearings =
company in a name like =E2=80=9Cprivate equity=E2=80=9D and suddenly it is =
legible to the Harvard students, so they flock to it.=09Those industries ar=
e also in the business of getting the ball bearings companies to accept the=
 Harvard Business School graduates, which in practice means not so much=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cmake the ball bearings company excited about its new Harvard CE=
O=E2=80=9D but rather=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cbuy the ball bearings company and insta=
ll new management.=E2=80=9DI don=E2=80=99t think this model is=C2=A0exactly=
=C2=A0right or anything, but I think there=E2=80=99s something to it. We ha=
ve talked a few times about =E2=80=9Csearch funds,=E2=80=9D which are a coo=
l way for graduates of prestigious business schools to say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=
=99m going into pest control.=E2=80=9D And I have suggested that =E2=80=9Cp=
rivate equity is sort of the industrial-scale version of this,=E2=80=9D in =
which top business school graduates get prestigious financial jobs that inv=
olve acquiring=C2=A0and running unglamorous industrial companies.So here=E2=
=80=99s a good Business Insider story from last week about how the most sou=
ght-after job at Harvard, Stanford and Wharton is running a plumbing compan=
y in Jackson, Mississippi:Data reviewed by Business Insider suggests San Fr=
ancisco-based Alpine Investors is quickly becoming one of the most sought-a=
fter places to work for graduates of top business schools. Driving the dema=
nd is Alpine's CEO-In-Training program, which places MBAs in leading positi=
ons at companies within just a few weeks and promises to turn them into act=
ual CEOs in a few years.For ambitious MBA students, the program offers the =
chance of a lifetime, although getting in is not easy. For the 2024 CIT pro=
gram, which starts this summer, Alpine received 750 applications for just 1=
2 slots, giving it an acceptance rate of 1.6%. Harvard, by contrast, has an=
 acceptance rate of about 3.6%. =E2=80=A6Success stories include David Wurt=
zbacher, who went from Harvard Business School to CFO of Alpine Investor's =
dental business to founding an Alpine-backed company that is rolling up loc=
al CPA firms in six years.In an interview with BI, Wurtzbacher described th=
e program as "turbocharged entrepreneurship." He said he received hands-on =
leadership training, but with the backbone of guaranteed funding, a large s=
upport network, and lessons on how to lead a business.And:The firm assesses=
 potential hires' intellectual curiosity, emotional intelligence, and, perh=
aps most importantly, their ability to handle adversity. It does this throu=
gh a series of short interviews, followed by a day-long interview for those=
 who make it past the first round.Grit is prized above all because even wit=
h the "sexy" job title of CEO or CFO, these jobs aren't stereotypically sex=
y. Instead of power lunches at posh Manhattan steakhouses, Alpine's CEOs in=
 training may be sent to small towns in rural America where they have to ge=
t their hands dirty."You're moving from Yale Law School and Harvard Busines=
s School to Jackson, Mississippi, to run a plumbing company," Anderman said=
 as an example.What are you doing after business school? Ah, I=E2=80=99m jo=
ining a prestigious private equity firm in San Francisco, to run their plum=
bing company in Mississippi.
 =20
   =20
      FTX claims
   =20
 =20
One story about crypto is that it does away with the need for trust. Code i=
s law, everything happens on a public immutable blockchain, and you don=E2=
=80=99t need to trust any central intermediary: You can=C2=A0prove=C2=A0tha=
t you own your Bitcoins by pointing to=C2=A0the blockchain.This was never q=
uite true, as a practical matter. Some crypto investors do organize their l=
ives around not having to trust anyone, but that is very inconvenient, and =
lots of crypto investors end up trusting people: You hold your crypto on a =
centralized=C2=A0exchange, not directly on a blockchain, and you=C2=A0trust=
 the exchange to hold it for you. Or you=C2=A0do=C2=A0hold your crypto on a=
 blockchain, and use it in decentralized applications, and you=C2=A0trust t=
hat the smart contracts you use do what they say they will,=C2=A0without ca=
refully auditing their code yourself.=C2=A0But it is possible that the phil=
osophical trustlessness of crypto is somehow corrosive to actual trustworth=
iness.=C2=A0A lot of crypto exchanges turned out=C2=A0not=C2=A0to be all th=
at trustworthy. If a stock exchange collapsed and took customer money with =
it, people would go around saying =E2=80=9Cwhere were the regulators=E2=80=
=9D and =E2=80=9Cwe need better rules to prevent that.=E2=80=9D When a cryp=
to exchange collapses, some people=C2=A0go around saying those things, but =
other people go around saying things like =E2=80=9Cnot your keys not your c=
oins=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cif you didn=E2=80=99t know that that exchange was=
 shady then really it=E2=80=99s your fault.=E2=80=9D Or when Avi Eisenberg =
spotted a profitable opportunity to manipulate the Mango Markets token, he =
did that, because he was philosophically committed to an ethos of code-is-l=
aw and trustlessness, though now he=E2=80=99s in jail.Similarly, if you are=
 used to anonymous, trustless international transactions, and if you think =
of those transactions as being subject not to any nation=E2=80=99s laws but=
 to =E2=80=9Ccode is law,=E2=80=9D and if you are used to transactions sett=
ling instantly on the blockchain, might you become =E2=80=A6=C2=A0untrustwo=
rthy? Might you agree to a trade, and then renege on the trade when prices =
move in your favor, and say =E2=80=9Cwell, that=E2=80=99s not a real trade,=
 it wasn=E2=80=99t even on the blockchain=E2=80=9D? I don=E2=80=99t know. T=
he Wall Street Journal reports:Since FTX=E2=80=99s 2022 implosion, hedge fu=
nds had scooped up the rights to customers=E2=80=99 frozen accounts for pen=
nies on the dollar, with five firms alone buying claims with a combined fac=
e value of about $2.4 billion. That meant a huge payday was in store.But co=
llecting these winnings won=E2=80=99t be straightforward. Investors are mir=
ed in legal battles with some of the original owners of the claims. They al=
lege those former FTX customers abruptly reneged on trades and are sufferin=
g from an age-old affliction: seller=E2=80=99s remorse.The FTX case has thr=
ust investment firms, some for the first time, into the Wild West of crypto=
. Compared to typical bankruptcy cases=E2=80=94where investors buy claims f=
rom relatively staid corporate creditors=E2=80=94firms this time are instea=
d cutting deals with crypto traders.=E2=80=9CWe have sellers from all over =
the world that are interfacing with buyers and the bankruptcy court for the=
 first time and have never experienced a U.S. Chapter 11 case,=E2=80=9D sai=
d Andrew Glantz, chief strategy officer of Xclaim, a platform that has faci=
litated more than $200 million of FTX claims transactions. ...Many sellers,=
 including some sophisticated crypto players, are now demanding bigger payo=
uts, according to court documents and people familiar with the matter. Othe=
rs have tried to back out entirely, or have tried to find other buyers to t=
ake their claims.FTX claims were trading at close to zero cents on the doll=
ar=C2=A0when FTX first went bankrupt, and are now likely to pay back at lea=
st 118 cents on the dollar.=C2=A0If you agreed to sell your claim at 30 cen=
ts on the dollar, but there was a long delay between the verbal agreement a=
nd finalizing the paperwork,=C2=A0then=C2=A0arguably=C2=A0you had=C2=A0a fr=
ee option: If the claim=E2=80=99s value fell to 20 cents, you=E2=80=99d clo=
se the deal and sell it for the 30 cents you agreed to, but if it rose to 5=
0 cents, you=E2=80=99d find a problem with the paperwork and get out of the=
 deal.
  [3]
=C2=A0And in fact it rose to 118 cents, and a lot of sellers seem to be try=
ing to get out of their deals. Also:Tom Braziel, a claims broker, sold tens=
 of millions of dollars of FTX claims to big investment firms like Oaktree =
Capital, Attestor and Silver Point Capital.He said many of the sellers don=
=E2=80=99t have lawyers and =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t realize that a verbal co=
ntract to sell a claim is binding under New York law, where most of these h=
edge funds are based.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Yes, right. One is tempted to say =E2=
=80=9Cif only these trades took place on the blockchain, then there would b=
e no dispute about who owned them: Settlement would be instantaneous, and t=
he claims would=C2=A0be tradeable tokens whose ownership could be proven ba=
sed on an open, tamper-proof blockchain.=E2=80=9D But of course people=C2=
=A0have=C2=A0tried to build tokenized platforms for trading crypto bankrupt=
cy claims. Most notably, the guys from Three Arrows Capital, the famously i=
mploded crypto hedge fund,=C2=A0were building one! Surely you trust them, r=
ight?
 =20
   =20
      AMC
   =20
 =20
It=E2=80=99s a little surprising that they are still doing this:AMC Enterta=
inment Holdings Inc. is holding confidential talks with some of its lenders=
 about lowering its debt load and extending near-term maturities, according=
 to people with knowledge of the matter.The discussions come as AMC, the wo=
rld=E2=80=99s largest movie theater chain, is staring down a debt load of a=
bout $4.5 billion of long-term borrowings. As of March 31, it had more than=
 $2.8 billion of maturities due in 2026, according to regulatory filings, i=
ncluding a $1.9 billion term loan and nearly $1 billion of second-lien note=
s.Negotiations are ongoing and no final decision has been made, the people =
said. A representative with AMC declined to comment, while messages left wi=
th Gibson Dunn & Crutcher, which is representing first-lien lenders, were n=
ot returned.=C2=A0I have been writing for=C2=A0years=C2=A0about how AMC is =
constantly using its meme-stock status to do=C2=A0big at-the-market stock o=
fferings at surprisingly high prices and using those offerings to pay down =
debt. (Or exchanging debt for equity, at those high meme-stock valuations.)=
 And yet there=E2=80=99s still so much debt.The worst-case outcome for a me=
me stock is Bed Bath & Beyond Inc.: You take a fundamentally nonviable busi=
ness with a negative net worth, you get a meme-stock lift, and you sell as =
much=C2=A0stock as you can to meme-stock investors to raise money to hand d=
irectly to creditors. At the end of the process, the meme-stock investors g=
et nothing, and the creditors get (1) the company, for whatever that=E2=80=
=99s worth, plus (2) the piles of cash raised from the meme-stock investors=
. My assumption is that AMC will use its long run as a meme stock to=C2=A0s=
olve=C2=A0its financial problems, but the alternative is bad.
 =20
   =20
      VC AI
   =20
 =20
It would be extremely funny if the first business automated out of existenc=
e by artificial intelligence is venture capital, but Business Insider repor=
ts:Silicon Valley has been enraptured by AI for the past two years, with VC=
s racing to fund all manner of AI startups. Now, AI is changing VC itself, =
making what was already a hard field to break into for young associates tha=
t much more difficult and impacting how early-stage startups are funded. =
=E2=80=A6James Currier, general partner at NFX, wrote a much-discussed colu=
mn last year laying out why he thinks the use of AI will level the playing =
field for venture investors in the next decade, just as software did for st=
ocks and bonds the last 40 years."Let's be honest: Much of what a typical v=
enture capitalist does=E2=80=94reading, summarizing, and ranking=E2=80=94is=
 what large language models already do extremely well," Currier wrote. "We =
are in the final 10 years of venture capital as we have come to know it. A.=
I. is going to remake the startup industrial complex, from its core. Ventur=
e firms will have to remake themselves into a combination of people and A.I=
."A lot of what is happening is that some of the lower-level analysis, targ=
eting and tracking work, which used to be done by junior venture capital as=
sociates, can now be done by AI. Instead of a few analysts doing the grunt =
work for a partner who is out befriending founders and leading investments,=
 now a robot does the grunt work and the partner does the deals and makes m=
ore money. Though, counterpoint:"They're already so small," said a partner =
at a large firm who asked to not to be identified, speaking in a vast confe=
rence room in their sleek and mostly empty San Francisco office. "Could you=
 have fewer people? To what end? You're making so much money as it is."But =
give it time! What value is the partner adding? Well:At its heart, venture =
is not about finding the best deals but winning them. That comes down to a =
personal connection between founder and investor, [Point72 Ventures=E2=80=
=99 Sri] Chandrasekar said."The No. 1 reason a founder chooses you is they =
want to work with you, specifically," he said. "You spend time building a r=
elationship with them. You have dinner with them. You meet their family =E2=
=80=94 whatever it is you need to do to make them feel like they really wan=
t to work with you for what you hope is a 10-year marriage."But we talked a=
 few years ago about how (1) venture capitalists, to stand out in a competi=
tive field, =E2=80=9Chave to build parasocial relationships with founders=
=E2=80=9D by being cool on Twitter (now X), because =E2=80=9CTwitter is the=
 new social club,=E2=80=9D and (2) therefore VCs hire ghostwriters to write=
 cool tweets for them. Surely a large language model could write tweets too=
. Venture capital is a process of funneling money from big institutions to =
promising founders with good business ideas, and then helping those founder=
s build their companies. If a robot can find the promising ideas and advise=
 the founders, maybe that process can be automated.
