10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Risk, returns</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a simple, bad financial produc=
t:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16=
px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You give me $100.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In a year, I give you back the return on the S&=
amp;P 500 stock index, but (1) if the index is=C2=A0<em>down</em>, you don=
=E2=80=99t lose any money and just get your $100 back, and (2) if the index=
 is up more than 5%, you only get the first 5% of returns. If the S&amp;P g=
oes up 3%, you get $103=C2=A0back. If it goes up 5%, you get $105. If it go=
es up 37%, you get $105. If it goes down 5%, you get $100. If it goes down =
37%, you get $100.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You have bought 10=
0% downside protection by giving away the upside above 105%.=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How do I manufacture this product? That is, how do =
I make sure that I have enough money in every scenario to pay you back? Wel=
l, I could probably do some stuff with options. But the simplest and most o=
bvious approach is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left:=
 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I use your $10=
0 to buy a one-year Treasury bill, which pays roughly 5.1% interest.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In a year I have $105.10.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">At that point, I look at the return on the S&a=
mp;P. If it=E2=80=99s 5% or more, I give you $105 and keep the remaining $0=
.10. If it=E2=80=99s zero or negative, I give you $100 and keep the remaini=
ng $5.10. In between, I give you $100 plus the S&amp;P=E2=80=99s return and=
 keep the rest.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is, like I said,=
 a very bad product. You should not buy it; you should just buy the Treasur=
y bill yourself instead. But the point I want to make is that=C2=A0three ye=
ars ago<em>=C2=A0</em>I could not have offered you even this product. Back =
then, the one-year Treasury rate was something like 0.08%. If I had wanted =
to offer you a product that was =E2=80=9Cthe S&amp;P return, but you can=E2=
=80=99t lose money and your upside is capped,=E2=80=9D the cap on your upsi=
de would have been, you know, 0.08%, which is even less exciting than 5%.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point is that for a long time in=
terest rates were very low, which means that if you wanted to make a return=
 on your money you needed to take stock-like risks: You could buy the S&amp=
;P 500, make money if it went up, and lose money if it went down. But now i=
nterest rates are considerably higher, which means that if you want to make=
 a (nominal) return on your money you can do that without taking any risk a=
t all.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing this means is that you can j=
ust buy bonds, but that=E2=80=99s boring. Another, much more fun thing that=
 it means is that <em>financial product designers</em>=C2=A0have a lot more=
 to work with. My product above is absurd, but you could use options to bui=
ld more plausible products, and if you do that, the fact that the risk-free=
 rate is 5% makes your product much more attractive than it would have been=
 at 0%. So <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3582117=
5.259288/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL2ludmVzdGluZy9yZXRpcmVlcy1ib2=
9tZXItY2FuZHktaW52ZXN0aW5nLWZ1bmQtNjI0NTQyMTA_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zMw/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB15afbe81" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the Wall Street Journal reports</a>:</=
p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even as signs of cooling inflati=
on have powered major indexes to new highs, investors have poured billions =
into exchange-traded funds that use derivatives to produce extra dividend i=
ncome or protect against losses.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Such funds=
, which were almost nonexistent four years ago, give retirees and other inv=
estors the chance to chase stock returns while also protecting against a po=
tential market slide. The funds have taken in at least $31 billion of new i=
nvestor money over the past 12 months, according to FactSet, bringing their=
 total assets to almost $120 billion. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">B=
uffer funds, another popular strategy that uses derivatives, claim to guard=
 against investor losses, up to a point, while limiting potential gains as =
well. A similar class of funds even advertises 100% downside protection, wh=
en certain conditions are met.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe =
like to call this kind of stuff =E2=80=98boomer candy,=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9D s=
aid Eric Balchunas, senior ETF analyst at Bloomberg Intelligence. =E2=80=9C=
They like being in the stock market but want the protection that helps you =
sleep at night. A good chunk of the ETF industry is in the lab trying to de=
sign more of these funds as we speak.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/35821175.259288/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjMtMDctMTkvYS1zdG9jay1mdW5kLXRoYXQtY2FuLXQtZ28tZG93bj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjI0=
MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1=
fdGVybT0yNDA2MjQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa=
37743ae" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">talked about the 100% downside protection funds</a> last s=
ummer. Schematically, the way to get 100% downside protection is to (1) tak=
e $100, (2) invest $95 in Treasury bills that will pay off $100 in a year, =
and (3) spend the remaining $5 buying options on the S&amp;P 500 that will =
pay off if the index goes up.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> This gives you some of the return of the S&amp;P 500, but with a guara=
nteed return of your principal. But when rates were zero, that sentence wou=
ld have read =E2=80=9C(1) take $100, (2) invest $100 in Treasury bills that=
 will pay off $100 in a year, and (3) that=E2=80=99s it, you=E2=80=99re out=
 of money, there=E2=80=99s no way to get anything like equity returns with =
no downside risk.=E2=80=9D Now there is.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In=
 some sense this is all sleight of hand. =E2=80=9CYou always get your money=
 back=E2=80=9D is a very=C2=A0<em>optically=C2=A0</em>attractive pitch, and=
 it is possible now in a way that it wasn=E2=80=99t three years ago. But it=
 is=C2=A0less <em>economically</em>=C2=A0attractive<em>=C2=A0</em>now than =
it was three years ago, because now the risk-free alternative is not =E2=80=
=9Cyou put in $100 and get back $100=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9Cyou put i=
n $100 and get back $105.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And with risk-free rates high, expe=
cted stock returns should also be high, so giving up upside is more costly:=
</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One such fund [retired financi=
al adviser Craig Morningstar] owns from First Trust tracks the Nasdaq-100. =
Over a rolling one-year period, the fund aims to protect against the first =
10% slide in the index, meaning that if Nasdaq-100 dropped 15%, the fund wo=
uld be down about 5%. Investor gains are capped at roughly 20%.=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But with the Nasdaq-100 up 37% over the past 12 =
months, buffer fund investors have missed out on substantial returns.</p></=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, you can see why the ETF indu=
stry is in the lab. The lab was so boring for so long, and now it isn=E2=80=
=99t. Investors got used to the idea that the only way to get a return=C2=
=A0was by owning stocks, so now they want to own stocks, but with less risk=
. And with interest rates higher, there are ways to do that.=C2=A0</p><tabl=
e class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" cellpadding=3D"0" c=
ellspacing=3D"0">
