</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It would be extremely funny if the fir=
st business automated out of existence by artificial intelligence is ventur=
e capital, but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/358=
21175.259288/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3NpbnNpZGVyLmNvbS9hcnRpZmljaWFsLWludG=
VsbGlnZW5jZS1pcy1jb21pbmctZm9yLXZlbnR1cmUtZmlybXMtMjAyNC02/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cBf6216b72" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">Business Insider reports</a>:</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Silicon Valley has been enraptured by AI for the =
past two years, with VCs racing to fund all manner of AI startups. Now, AI =
is changing VC itself, making what was already a hard field to break into f=
or young associates that much more difficult and impacting how early-stage =
startups are funded. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">James Currie=
r, general partner at NFX, wrote a much-discussed column last year laying o=
ut why he thinks the use of AI will level the playing field for venture inv=
estors in the next decade, just as software did for stocks and bonds the la=
st 40 years.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"Let's be honest: Much of what=
 a typical venture capitalist does=E2=80=94reading, summarizing, and rankin=
g=E2=80=94is what large language models already do extremely well," Currier=
 wrote. "We are in the final 10 years of venture capital as we have come to=
 know it. A.I. is going to remake the startup industrial complex, from its =
core. Venture firms will have to remake themselves into a combination of pe=
ople and A.I."</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lot of what i=
s happening is that some of the lower-level analysis, targeting and trackin=
g work, which used to be done by junior venture capital associates, can now=
 be done by AI. Instead of a few analysts doing the grunt work for a partne=
r who is out befriending founders and leading investments, now a robot does=
 the grunt work and the partner does the deals and makes more money. Though=
, counterpoint:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"They're alread=
y so small," said a partner at a large firm who asked to not to be identifi=
ed, speaking in a vast conference room in their sleek and mostly empty San =
Francisco office. "Could you have fewer people? To what end? You're making =
so much money as it is."</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But g=
ive it time! What value is the partner adding? Well:</p><blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At its heart, venture is not about finding the best d=
eals but winning them. That comes down to a personal connection between fou=
nder and investor, [Point72 Ventures=E2=80=99 Sri] Chandrasekar said.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"The No. 1 reason a founder chooses you is they =
want to work with you, specifically," he said. "You spend time building a r=
elationship with them. You have dinner with them. You meet their family =E2=
=80=94 whatever it is you need to do to make them feel like they really wan=
t to work with you for what you hope is a 10-year marriage."</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/35821175.259288/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMTMvdmNzLW5lZWQtdGhlLWdvb2QtdHdlZXRzP2NtcGlkPU=
